---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../components/CodeExample.astro';
import HubCard from '../../../components/HubCard.astro';
import MigrationEffort from '../../../components/MigrationEffort.astro';
import MigrationMilestones from '../../../components/MigrationMilestones.astro';
import MigrationSteps from '../../../components/MigrationSteps.astro';
import {
    migrationEffortTiers,
    migrationMilestones,
    migrationPathSteps
} from '../../../data/migration';

const layerOrderExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;

const legacyImportExample = `@import './legacy/site.css' layer(legacy);
@import './components/product-card.css' layer(components);`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Migration"
    description="Migrating existing projects toward Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Apply</p>

        <h1>
            Migrating existing CSS
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Good migration is not heroic rewrites. It is controlled improvement.
            You should not need to pause delivery, rebuild the whole frontend,
            or pretend the old CSS is not still in the room.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Migration sections">
        <a href="#first-decision">Start first</a>
        <a href="#principles">Principles</a>
        <a href="#path">Recommended path</a>
        <a href="#milestones">Milestones</a>
        <a href="#effort">Effort</a>
        <a href="#legacy">Legacy layer</a>
        <a href="#avoid">What not to do</a>
    </nav>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="first-decision">
            Ask this first
        </h2>

        <p>
            <strong>Ask first:</strong> Can this be safely replaced now?
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Yes</strong> — replace properly.</li>
            <li><strong>No</strong> — contain it and improve around it.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Most migration mistakes come from trying to fix everything at once.
            Decide whether the code should be replaced or safely contained.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="principles">
            Migration principles
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard title="Contain first">
                <p>
                    Put existing CSS somewhere predictable before changing how
                    new CSS is written.
                </p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard title="Improve active code">
                <p>
                    Fix the CSS people touch every week, not the fossil no one
                    has opened since 2018.
                </p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard title="Delete over time">
                <p>
                    Migration succeeds when legacy CSS gets smaller, not when it
                    gets renamed and promoted.
                </p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="path">
            Recommended migration path
        </h2>

        <p>
            Work through the steps in order. Skip ahead only when a later step does
            not depend on the foundation you have not laid yet.
        </p>

        <MigrationSteps steps={migrationPathSteps} />

        <h3 id="milestones">
            Common migration milestones
        </h3>

        <p>
            Use these checkpoints in planning and retrospectives. They describe
            outcomes, not calendar dates.
        </p>

        <MigrationMilestones milestones={migrationMilestones} />

        <h3 id="effort">
            Expected effort range
        </h3>

        <p>
            Timelines vary with legacy surface area and how often teams ship. Treat
            ranges as planning guides, not deadlines.
        </p>

        <MigrationEffort tiers={migrationEffortTiers} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Step 1: define the cascade order
        </h2>

        <p>
            Add layer order before moving code. This gives the project a stable
            override model immediately and stops specificity wars from breeding.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={layerOrderExample} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="legacy">
            Step 2: isolate legacy CSS
        </h2>

        <p>
            Inherited first-party CSS belongs in the <code>legacy</code> layer so
            the rest of the project can move forward without pretending old code is
            modern architecture. If vendor CSS is separate, use an optional
            <code>thirdparty</code> layer declared <strong>before</strong>
            <code>legacy</code> in the <code>@layer</code> list — see
            <a href="/apply/layers/#legacy">legacy and third-party layers</a>.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={legacyImportExample} />

        <p>
            Importing old CSS into the correct low layer means every intentional
            layer above it has clearer ownership and safer override behaviour.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="avoid">
            What not to do
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Do not rename every class and call it migration.</li>
            <li>Do not move legacy CSS into components and call it clean.</li>
            <li>Do not let hacks become permanent architecture.</li>
            <li>Do not add specificity when layer order solves the problem.</li>
            <li>Do not block delivery for a rewrite plan with no clear business case.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Migration should reduce risk, not create a dramatic new source of it.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Definition of done
        </h2>

        <p>
            Migration is working when new CSS follows the system, old CSS is
            contained, overrides are predictable, and the legacy layer keeps
            shrinking over time.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Next useful pages
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard href="/apply/starter-template/" title="Starter template">
                <p>See what good structure looks like once legacy CSS is isolated.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/apply/layers/" title="Layers">
                <p>Understand the cascade order first, because migration starts with precedence control.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/apply/hacks/" title="Hacks">
                <p>Separate temporary fixes from real architecture while legacy code is being reduced.</p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
